<subsection xml:id="sec-intro-to-ellipses">
  <title>Brief Introduction to Ellipse</title>

  <introduction>
    <p>
      An ellipse is a type of <term>conic section</term>, a shape resulting from intersecting a plane with a cone and looking at the curve where they intersect. They were discovered by the Greek mathematician Menaechmus over two millennia ago.
    </p>
    <p>
  
        The figure below<fn>
        Pbroks13 (<url href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Conic_sections_with_plane.svg" visual="commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Conic_sections_with_plane.svg">Wikimedia Commons</url>), 
        <q>Conic sections with plane</q>, cropped to show only ellipse and circle by L Michaels, 
      </fn> shows two types of conic sections. When a plane is perpendicular to the axis of the cone, the shape of the intersection is a circle. A slightly tilted plane creates an oval-shaped conic section called an <term>ellipse</term>.
      </p>

    <figure xml:id="fig-conic-sections-intro">
      <caption>Conic sections resulting from a plane intersecting a cone.</caption>
      <image source="graphics/conic.png" />
      <!--<description>A diagram showing a plane intersecting a cone to create a circle and an ellipse.</description>
      -->
      
    </figure>
  </introduction>
  </subsection>
<subsection xml:id="sec-ellipse-definition-vocabulary">
  <title>Ellipse Definition and Vocabulary</title>

  <p>
    An <term>ellipse</term> is the set of all points <m>Q(x, y)</m> for which the sum of the distance to two fixed points <m>F_1(x_1, y_1)</m> and <m>F_2(x_2, y_2)</m>, called the <term>foci</term> (plural of focus), is a constant <m>k</m>:
    <me>d(Q, F_1) + d(Q, F_2) = k</me>
  </p>

  <figure xml:id="ellipse-definition-figure">
      <caption>Conic sections resulting from a plane intersecting a cone.</caption>
      <image xml:id="image-ellipse-definition" >
      <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]
      % Draw the Axes
      \draw[thick, ->] (-4.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
      \draw[thick, ->] (0,-3) -- (0,3) node[above] {$y$};

      % Draw the Ellipse (a=4, b=2.2)
      \draw[ultra thick, blue!80!black] (0,0) ellipse (4cm and 2.2cm);

      % Define Foci (c = sqrt(4^2 - 2.2^2) approx 3.34)
      \coordinate (F1) at (3.34,0);
      \coordinate (F2) at (-3.34,0);
      \coordinate (Q) at (1.5, 2.04); % A point on the ellipse

      % Draw the dashed lines to point Q
      \draw[thick, dashed, red!70!black] (F2) -- (Q) node[midway, above left] {$d(Q,F_2)$};
      \draw[thick, dashed, red!70!black] (F1) -- (Q) node[midway, above right] {$d(Q,F_1)$};

      % Draw the points with updated labels
      \fill (F1) circle (3pt) node[below=5pt] {$F_1(c,0)$};
      \fill (F2) circle (3pt) node[below=5pt] {$F_2(-c,0)$};
      \fill (Q) circle (4pt) node[above right] {$Q(x,y)$};

    \end{tikzpicture}
      <!--<description>A diagram showing a plane intersecting a cone to create a circle and an ellipse.</description>
      -->
     </latex-image> 
     </image>
    </figure>

  <p>
    To graph and describe ellipses, we use the following standard vocabulary:
    <ul label="disc">
      <li>
        <p>The <term>major axis</term> is the line segment passing through the foci with endpoints on the ellipse.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p><term>Vertices</term> are the points where the ellipse intersects the major axis.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>The <term>center</term> is the midpoint between the vertices (or the midpoint between the foci).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>The <term>minor axis</term> is the line segment perpendicular to the major axis passing through the center with endpoints on the ellipse.</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>The endpoints of the minor axis are called <term>co-vertices</term> (or minor axis endpoints).</p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>The <term>major axis length</term> and <term>minor axis length</term> refer to the total distance between their respective endpoints.</p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <p>
  Ellipse orientation is determined by the 
  placement of the major axis. We typically focus on the two standard cases: 
  a <term>horizontal orientation</term> and a <term>vertical orientation</term> as shown in the figures below.
</p>
