<subsection xml:id="derivation">
    <title>Derivation of Standard Equation of an Ellipse</title>
    
    <p>
      From the definition the ellipse we can find an equation for an ellipse centered at origin <m>C(0,0)</m> with foci at <m>F_1(c,0)</m> and <m>F_2(-c,0)</m> where <m>c \gt 0</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Suppose <m>Q(x,y)</m> is some point on the ellipse. The distance from <m>F_1</m> to <m>Q</m> is given by
      <me>d(Q,F_1) = \sqrt{(x-c)^2 + (y-0)^2} = \sqrt{(x-c)^2 + y^2}</me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Likewise, the distance from <m>F_2</m> to <m>Q</m> is given by
      <me>d(Q,F_2) = \sqrt{(x-(-c))^2 + (y-0)^2} = \sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2}</me>
    </p>

    <p>
  From the definition of the ellipse, the sum of these distances should be constant: 
  <m>d(Q,F_1) + d(Q,F_2) = k</m> so that
  <men xml:id="eqn-ellipse-sum">
    \sqrt{(x-c)^2 + y^2} + \sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} = k
  </men>
  </p>

    <p>
      If we label one of the vertices <m>(a,0)</m>, it should satisfy the equation above since it is a point on the ellipse. This allows us to write <m>k</m> in terms of <m>a</m>.
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow>\sqrt{(a-c)^2 + 0^2} + \sqrt{(a+c)^2 + 0^2} \amp = k</mrow>
      <mrow>|a-c| + |a+c| \amp = k \amp\amp \text{Since } a \gt c \text{, these will be positive}</mrow>
      <mrow>(a-c) + (a+c) \amp = k</mrow>
      <mrow>2a \amp = k</mrow>
    </md>

    <p>
      Plugging <m>k = 2a</m> into equation <xref ref="eqn-ellipse-sum" /> yields:
    </p>

    <md>
      <mrow>\sqrt{(x-c)^2 + y^2} + \sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} \amp = 2a</mrow>
      <mrow>\sqrt{(x-c)^2 + y^2} \amp = 2a - \sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2}</mrow>
      <mrow>\left(\sqrt{(x-c)^2 + y^2}\right)^2 \amp = \left(2a - \sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2}\right)^2 </mrow>
      <mrow>(x-c)^2 + y^2 \amp = 4a^2 - 4a\sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} + (x+c)^2 + y^2 </mrow>
      <mrow>x^2 - 2xc + c^2 + y^2 \amp = 4a^2 - 4a\sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} + x^2 + 2xc + c^2 + y^2</mrow>
    </md>
    <p>
      Combining like terms and isolating the radical yields:
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>4a\sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} \amp = 4a^2 + 4xc </mrow>
        <mrow>a\sqrt{(x+c)^2 + y^2} \amp = a^2 + xc </mrow>
        <mrow>a^2 \left( (x+c)^2 + y^2 \right) \amp = a^4 + 2a^2xc + x^2c^2</mrow>
        <mrow>a^2(x^2 + 2xc + c^2 + y^2) \amp = a^4 + 2a^2xc + x^2c^2 </mrow>
        <mrow>a^2x^2 + 2a^2xc + a^2c^2 + a^2y^2 \amp = a^4 + 2a^2xc + x^2c^2 </mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
    Seperating the terms with variables on the left and contants on the right gives:
    </p>
    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>a^2x^2 - x^2c^2 + a^2y^2 \amp = a^4 - a^2c^2 </mrow>
        <mrow>(a^2 - c^2)x^2 + a^2y^2 \amp = a^2(a^2 - c^2)</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Let <m>b^2 = a^2 - c^2</m>. Since <m>a \gt c</m>, we know <m>b \gt 0</m>. Substituting <m>b^2</m> for <m>a^2 - c^2</m> leaves:
    </p>

    <p>
      <md>
        <mrow>b^2x^2 + a^2y^2 \amp = a^2b^2 </mrow>
        <mrow>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} \amp = 1</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      This is the standard equation for an ellipse. We typically swap <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> when the major axis of the ellipse is vertical.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-standard-forms-origin">
    <title>Key Features of Ellipses Centered at the Origin</title>
  
  <p>
  The following table summarizes the key properties of ellipses centered at the origin <m>(0,0)</m> based on the orientation of the major axis. In these formulas, we assume <m>a \gt b \gt 0</m>, where the length of the major axis is <m>2a</m> and the length of the minor axis is <m>2b</m>.
</p>
    
    <tabular top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium">
      <row header="yes">
        <cell></cell>
        <cell>Major axis: <m>x</m>-axis</cell>
        <cell>Major axis: <m>y</m>-axis</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Equation:</cell>
        <cell><m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1</m></cell>
        <cell><m>\frac{x^2}{b^2} + \frac{y^2}{a^2} = 1</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Center:</cell>
        <cell><m>(0, 0)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(0, 0)</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Foci: (<m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m>)</cell>
        <cell><m>(c, 0)</m> and <m>(-c, 0)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(0, c)</m> and <m>(0, -c)</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Vertices: Endpoints of major axis</cell>
        <cell><m>(a, 0)</m> and <m>(-a, 0)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(0, a)</m> and <m>(0, -a)</m></cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Endpoints of minor axis</cell>
        <cell><m>(0, b)</m> and <m>(0, -b)</m></cell>
        <cell><m>(b, 0)</m> and <m>(-b, 0)</m></cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>
  </subsection> 

  <!-- Example  -->

  <example xml:id="ex-ellipse-1" number="9.1.1">
  <!-- <title>Graphing an Ellipse Centered at the Origin</title> -->
  <statement>
    <p>
      Graph the ellipse and identify the center, foci, and vertices for the equation:
      <me>\frac{x^2}{25} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      First, we identify that the ellipse is centered at the origin <m>(0,0)</m>. 
      Comparing the given equation to the standard form <m>\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1</m>, 
      we see that <m>a^2 = 25</m> and <m>b^2 = 4</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Since <m>a^2 \gt b^2</m>, the major axis is horizontal. We find the following key values:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>a = \sqrt{25} = 5</m>, so the <term>vertices</term> are at <m>(\pm 5, 0)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>b = \sqrt{4} = 2</m>, so the <term>co-vertices</term> are at <m>(0, \pm 2)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            To find the <term>foci</term>, we use <m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m>:
            <me>c^2 = 25 - 4 = 21 \implies c = \sqrt{21}</me>
            The foci are located at <m>(\pm \sqrt{21}, 0)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    <!-- <figure xml:id="fig-ellipse-with-covertices">
  <caption>The ellipse <m>\frac{x^2}{25} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1</m> with all key points labeled.</caption> -->
  <image xml:id="img-ellipse-full-labels">
    <latex-image>
      \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
        % Grid and Axes
        \draw[help lines, gray!20] (-6,-4) grid (6,4);
        \draw[thick, ->] (-6.5,0) -- (6.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
        \draw[thick, ->] (0,-3.5) -- (0,3.5) node[above] {$y$};

        % The Ellipse
        \draw[very thick, blue] (0,0) ellipse (5 and 2);

        % Vertices (a=5)
        \filldraw[black] (5,0) circle (2pt) node[below right] {$(5,0)$};
        \filldraw[black] (-5,0) circle (2pt) node[below left] {$(-5,0)$};

        % Co-vertices (b=2)
        \filldraw[red] (0,2) circle (2pt) node[above right] {$(0,2)$};
        \filldraw[red] (0,-2) circle (2pt) node[below right] {$(0,-2)$};

        % Foci (c=sqrt(21) approx 4.58)
        \filldraw[darkgray] (4.58,0) circle (1.5pt) node[above] {$F_1$};
        \filldraw[darkgray] (-4.58,0) circle (1.5pt) node[above] {$F_2$};

        % Center
        \filldraw (0,0) circle (1.5pt) node[below left] {$(0,0)$};
      \end{tikzpicture}
    </latex-image>
  </image>
<!-- </figure> -->
  </solution>
</example>

