<!-- Example 2 -->

  <example xml:id="ex-graph-vertical-ellipse">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Graph the ellipse and identify the center, foci, and vertices:
      <me>49x^2 + 9y^2 = 441</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      First, we rewrite the equation in standard form by dividing both sides by <m>441</m>:
      <me>\frac{x^2}{9} + \frac{y^2}{49} = 1</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      From this form, we identify the following:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>The center is at the origin <m>(0, 0)</m>.</p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            Since the larger denominator is under the <m>y</m> term, the major axis is vertical. 
            With <m>a^2 = 49</m>, the <term>vertices</term> are <m>(0, 7)</m> and <m>(0, -7)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            With <m>b^2 = 9</m>, the <term>co-vertices</term> are <m>(3, 0)</m> and <m>(-3, 0)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            The distance to the <term>foci</term> is <m>c = \sqrt{49 - 9} = \sqrt{40} \approx 6.32</m>. 
            The foci are <m>(0, \pm\sqrt{40})</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>

