  <!-- example -->
  <example xml:id="ex-ellipse-general-to-standard">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Write the equation of the ellipse in standard form. Identify the center, foci, and vertices.
      <me>9x^2 + 5y^2 + 18x - 30y + 9 = 0</me>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      First, group the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> terms and move the constant to the right side:
      <me>9(x^2 + 2x) + 5(y^2 - 6y) = -9</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Complete the square for both variables:
      <me>9(x^2 + 2x + 1) + 5(y^2 - 6y + 9) = -9 + 9(1) + 5(9)</me>
      <me>9(x + 1)^2 + 5(y - 3)^2 = 45</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Divide by 45 to obtain the standard form:
      <me>\frac{(x + 1)^2}{5} + \frac{(y - 3)^2}{9} = 1</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      From this form, we identify:
      <ul>
        <li><p>The center is <m>(h, k) = (-1, 3)</m>.</p></li>
        <li><p>The major axis is vertical since <m>9 > 5</m>.</p></li>
        <li>
          <p>
            With <m>a=3</m> and <m>c = \sqrt{9-5} = 2</m>, the vertices are <m>(-1, 6)</m> and <m>(-1, 0)</m>, and the foci are <m>(-1, 5)</m> and <m>(-1, 1)</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
