<subsection xml:id="sec-eccentricity-ellipse">
  <title>Determine and Apply the Eccentricity of an Ellipse</title>

  <definition xml:id="def-eccentricity-ellipse">
    <title>Eccentricity of an Ellipse</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        The degree of elongation of an ellipse is measured by the <term>eccentricity</term>, <m>e</m>, of the ellipse.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </definition>

  <p>
    For an ellipse defined by 
    <me>\frac{(x-h)^2}{a^2} + \frac{(y-k)^2}{b^2} = 1 \text{ or } \frac{(x-h)^2}{b^2} + \frac{(y-k)^2}{a^2} = 1</me>, 
    the <term>eccentricity</term>, <m>e</m>, is given by 
    <me>e = \frac{c}{a}</me> 
    where <m>a \gt b \gt 0</m>, <m>c \gt 0</m>, and <m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m>.
  </p>

  <p>
    The eccentricity of an ellipse is a number between 0 and 1. That is, <m>0 \lt e \lt 1</m>.
  </p>
  <remark xml:id="remark-ellipse-eccentricity">
    <p>
        If the foci are near the vertices (that is, <m>a</m> is only slightly greater 
        than <m>c</m>), then the ellipse is more elongated. 
        If the foci are near the center, then the ellipse is more circular.
    </p>
</remark>
</subsection>
<example xml:id="ex-ellipse-eccentricity">
  <statement>
    <p>Determine the eccentricity of the following ellipses.</p>
    <sidebyside widths="45% 45%">
      <p><me>\frac{x^2}{225} + \frac{y^2}{9} = 1</me></p>
      <p><me>\frac{x^2}{9} + \frac{y^2}{4} = 1</me></p>
    </sidebyside>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      For the first ellipse, <m>a^2 = 225</m> and <m>b^2 = 9</m>. 
      Then <m>c = \sqrt{225-9} = \sqrt{216} = 6\sqrt{6}</m>.
      The eccentricity is <m>e = \frac{6\sqrt{6}}{15} = \frac{2\sqrt{6}}{5} \approx 0.98</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      For the second ellipse, <m>a^2 = 9</m> and <m>b^2 = 4</m>. 
      Then <m>c = \sqrt{9-4} = \sqrt{5}</m>.
      The eccentricity is <m>e = \frac{\sqrt{5}}{3} \approx 0.745</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
<!-- try it example -->
<exercise xml:id="ez-try-it-eccentricity">
    <title>Try It</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Determine the eccentricity of the ellipse given by the equation:
            <me>\frac{x^2}{16} + \frac{y^2}{25} = 1</me>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
        <p>
            First, identify <m>a^2</m> and <m>b^2</m>. Remember that <m>a^2</m> is always the larger denominator. Then use the formula <m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m> to find the focal distance.
        </p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <m>e = \frac{3}{5} = 0.6</m>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            In this equation, the larger denominator is under <m>y^2</m>, so <m>a^2 = 25</m> and <m>b^2 = 16</m>. 
            This means the ellipse is vertical.
        </p>
        <p>
            First, we find <m>c</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>c^2 \amp = a^2 - b^2</mrow>
                <mrow>c^2 \amp = 25 - 16 = 9</mrow>
                <mrow>c \amp = 3</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Now, we calculate the eccentricity <m>e</m>:
            <me>e = \frac{c}{a} = \frac{3}{5} = 0.6</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>

<!-- example -->
<example xml:id="ex-ellipse-from-vertices-eccentricity">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Write the standard form of the equation of an ellipse with vertices <m>(-6, 7)</m> and <m>(2,7)</m> and eccentricity <m>\frac{3}{4}</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      First, we find the center <m>(h,k)</m> by calculating the midpoint of the vertices:
      <me>h = \frac{-6 + 2}{2} = -2, \quad k = 7</me>
      The center is <m>(-2, 7)</m>. Since the vertices have the same <m>y</m>-coordinate, the major axis is horizontal.
    </p>
    <p>
      The distance from the center <m>(-2, 7)</m> to the vertex <m>(2, 7)</m> gives the semi-major axis <m>a</m>:
      <me>a = 2 - (-2) = 4</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      We use the eccentricity <m>e = \frac{3}{4}</m> to find <m>c</m>:
      <me>\frac{c}{a} = \frac{3}{4} \implies \frac{c}{4} = \frac{3}{4} \implies c = 3</me>
    </p>
    <p>
      Now find <m>b^2</m> using the relationship <m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m>:
      <md>
        <mrow>3^2 \amp = 4^2 - b^2</mrow>
        <mrow>9 \amp = 16 - b^2</mrow>
        <mrow>b^2 \amp = 7</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>
    <p>
      The standard form of the equation is:
      <me>\frac{(x + 2)^2}{16} + \frac{(y - 7)^2}{7} = 1</me>
    </p>
  </solution>
</example>
