<exercise xml:id="ez-try-it-ellipse-vertices-ecc">
    <title>Try It</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Find the standard form of the equation of the ellipse with vertices <m>(3, -4)</m> and <m>(3, 6)</m> and eccentricity <m>e = \frac{4}{5}</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <hint>
        <p>
            Start by finding the center of the ellipse, which is the midpoint between the two vertices. Then determine the distance <m>a</m> from the center to a vertex and use the eccentricity formula <m>e = \frac{c}{a}</m> to find <m>c</m>.
        </p>
    </hint>
    <answer>
        <p>
            <me>\frac{(x - 3)^2}{9} + \frac{(y - 1)^2}{25} = 1</me>
        </p>
    </answer>
    <solution>
        <p>
            First, find the center <m>(h,k)</m> by finding the midpoint of the vertices <m>(3, -4)</m> and <m>(3, 6)</m>:
            <me>h = 3, \quad k = \frac{-4 + 6}{2} = 1</me>
            The center is <m>(3, 1)</m>. Since the <m>x</m>-coordinates of the vertices are the same, the major axis is vertical.
        </p>
        <p>
            The distance from the center <m>(3, 1)</m> to the vertex <m>(3, 6)</m> gives the semi-major axis length:
            <me>a = 6 - 1 = 5</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Next, we use the eccentricity <m>e = \frac{c}{a}</m> to find the value of <m>c</m>:
            <me>\frac{4}{5} = \frac{c}{5} \implies c = 4</me>
        </p>
        <p>
            Now, find <m>b^2</m> using the relationship <m>c^2 = a^2 - b^2</m>:
            <md>
                <mrow>4^2 \amp = 5^2 - b^2</mrow>
                <mrow>16 \amp = 25 - b^2</mrow>
                <mrow>b^2 \amp = 9</mrow>
            </md>
        </p>
        <p>
            Because the ellipse has a vertical major axis, the value <m>a^2</m> belongs under the <m>y</m> term:
            <me>\frac{(x - 3)^2}{9} + \frac{(y - 1)^2}{25} = 1</me>
        </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>
